        "rating": 1,
        "relativeTimeDescription": "a year ago",
        "text": "Terrible experience - we toured the facility and they seemed great. One week prior to starting, I inquired about if they had air conditioning, and if not, how they ensured the health and safety of the children in regards to not overheating (it was during a heat wave). I was informed that they did not have any \"fancy temperature measuring devices\" and that no parents had every inquired about it before. If it was hot, they moved in a portable air conditioning unit or opened windows. They determined if it was hot by if the teachers were hot or not. They had no policies in place regarding acceptable temperature ranges for inside (they had rules around outside), nor digital thermometers in the class rooms. I highlighted to them that Calgary had several heat waves over the last two summers, and that other child care facilities that I contacted (including our current one) had air conditioning and a clear policy on the health and safety of the children during heat waves. I was fine with them not having air conditioning, but I needed to know that the room could be maintained at a safe temperature. They could not tell me what the maximum or average temperatures would be in the room, during heat waves.\n\nAfter a bit of back and forth, I was informed that it was clear I didn't trust them enough to care for my child, so we were not suited for their facility, and they returned my deposit. This left me scrambling to find child care with one week's notice. In discussing this with licensing and health, I was assured that this was a legitimate issue to be inquiring on.\n\nNo child care provider will have my blind trust, and I would expect that every provider would be able to answer basic health and safety questions. Thankfully I was able to get into an alternative facility that was not at all put off when I inquired about how they ensured the health and safety of my child when in their care. Heat waves are a normal part of Calgary summers now, and excessive heat exposure for vulnerable persons (inc children) can be a significant health threat. I am super glad that we are not going to be attending a facility that expects my blind trust when unable to address what should be a simple question (ie. yes, we have digital thermometers in each room, and ensure that they temperature is maintained below 28 degrees during heat waves).",
